[2] Cholera - Zambia
Date: Thu, 26 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The Post (Lusaka) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200601260245.html>

Over 70 new cases of suspected cholera have been recorded in the country in
the last 2 days. Health minister Sylvia Masebo on Tue, 24 Jan 2006, said
as at 24 Jan 2006, there were 3 070 cases recorded from the time of the
outbreak. On the previous day, Ministry of Health Permanent Secretary Dr
Simon Miti had confirmed a record of about 2 926 suspected cholera cases as
of that day.
Masebo said 339 cases had been recorded in Central Province, two in
Kasempa, while Copperbelt had 122. According to Masebo, Southern Province
had 55 and Luapula Province recorded 21 from the time the disease broke out
last August.
"From 21 Aug 2005 to date (24 Jan 2006) 3 070 have been recorded for
suspected and cholera cases, 19 deaths, 14 BIDs (Brought In Dead) while 207
are currently under treatment," Masebo said.
She expressed concern over the high number of cases being recorded in
Lusaka. "People visiting Lusaka should be careful and avoid unnecessary
movements," she said.
Masebo appealed to the public to avoid making statements on cholera unless
they were verified. She said only district and provincial health directors
and Ministry of Health officials could comment to avoid giving wrong
information which could cause unnecessary alarm.
[Byline: Sandra Lombe]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
