[3] Cholera - Zambia
Date: Mon, 23 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters, South Africa [edited]
<http://za.today.reuters.com/news/NewsArticle.aspx?type=topNews&storyID=2006-01-23T105113Z_01_BAN339124_RTRIDST_0_OZATP-HEALTH-ZAMBIA-CHOLERA-20060123.XML>

25 people have been killed in a cholera outbreak in Zambia in Jan 2006,
state radio and the health ministry said on Mon, 23 Jan 2006. 5 members
from 1 family and 5 prisoners had been felled by the disease near the
southern town of Mazabuka - 120 km (75 miles) from the capital Lusaka -
adding to another 15 that died earlier in the month, the newspapers and
health ministry said.
Some 2721 had been admitted to state hospitals suffering from cholera,
officials said. Simon Miti, permanent secretary in the health ministry,
confirmed 15 deaths while a minister and a junior official in Miti's
department reported the additional 10. "A school has been closed and all
pupils sent home after 5 members of a family died of cholera at Chikani in
Mazabuka," state radio reported on Mon, 23 Jan 2006.
Cholera deaths have also been reported in neighboring Zimbabwe and Malawi
in Jan 2006. Southern African countries are most vulnerable to the disease
at this time of year during the summer rains.
--
