[4] Cholera, dysentery - Zambia (Southern Province)
Date: Mon, 23 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Zambian Post [edited]
<http://www.andnetwork.com/app?service=direct/0/Home/$StorySummary$0.$DirectLink$2&sp=l13709>

Another cholera patient has been admitted to Chikani Primary School in
Mazabuka bringing the total number of patients to 8. Acting health
district director Gideon Mwiche revealed this during an emergency epidemic
meeting yesterday, 22 Jan 2006.
He also disclosed that dysentery had broken out in Chikani area and that 3
patients were admitted to the school but isolated from cholera patients.
Dr Mwiche attributed the outbreak to poor sanitation. He said that unless
villagers were educated on the need to observe hygiene, outbreaks of
epidemics would continue haunting the area. Dr Mwiche, however, said
health personnel had embarked on disinfecting homesteads for cholera
patients to limit the spread of the disease. He also said Ministry of
Health had sent enough chlorine for distribution to all affected villages.
Dr Mwiche said investigations carried out by his office revealed that the
1st cholera patient died on 10 Jan 2006 and family members ignorantly went
ahead with the without knowing the implications of the disease. He named
the affected villages as Kasaka and Samboko of Chikani and Simwambwa areas.
He also said district health officials had held an emergency meeting with
village headmen in affected areas to help sensitise their subjects on the
epidemic.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
